	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I highly doubt that at the time in Japan artists had any rights for their works if they worked for a company. It is much more probably that Hudson own the rights to the music.
<br />
<br />I wonder, why you need to use music from the original or composed by the original composer. There are people who like to mimic styles of other composers, making new music that sounds very similar to one made by the other composers, but obviously, no third party rights involved in this case. Related to NES, it mostly happens with Capcom music from Mega Man, a LOT of people mimic the style, but I'm sure, you'll be able to find people who want to mimic Adventure Island music as well.
<br />
<br />There also was a guy who made <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/Shnabubula#g/c/FBDD461401CA70E1" class="postlink">series of very authentic 'alternative soundtracks'</a> for NES games. His nickname is Shnabubula, you may try to contact with him, for example.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


